                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815650,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174685/650/11815650.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"200\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815651,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174684/651/11815651.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815652,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T141805+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:18 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": null,\n                    \"caption\": \"Quenched was advertising with the phrase: Don’t stop the party at your place early, we are here to help.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815652,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174685/652/11815652.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"220\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815653,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T141805+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:18 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": null,\n                    \"caption\": \"Quenched was advertising with the phrase: Don’t stop the party at your place early, we are here to help.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815653,\n                            \"layout\": \"ipad section splash 956:956\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174685/653/11815653.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"953\",\n                            \"height\": \"956\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68741060,\n            \"path\": \"/sport/other-sports/68741060/Dean-Barker-named-CEO-skipper-for-Japans-Americas-Cup-entry\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/sport/other-sports/68741060/Dean-Barker-named-CEO-skipper-for-Japans-Americas-Cup-entry\",\n            \"section\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"section-home\": \"Other Sports\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Sport\",\n            \"layout\": \"landscape-image\",\n            \"title\": \"Dean Barker named CEO, skipper for Japan's America's Cup entry\",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"Barker CEO, skipper of new entry\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T141138+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"14:11 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": \"DUNCAN JOHNSTONE\",\n            \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n            \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"category_id\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"stream_id\": \"stuff/sport/other-sports/68741060\",\n            \"intro\": \"Dean Barker has been appointed skipper and CEO of Japan's America's Cup challenge.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"Dumped Team New Zealand skipper to take the helm of Japan's entry in the next America's Cup.\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>Dean Barker has been appointed skipper and CEO of Japan's America's Cup challenge.</p> <p>It's a massive rebound for the Kiwi sailing veteran who was axed as helmsman by Team New Zealand earlier this year, leaving the syndicate in a bitter split.</p> <p>&quot;This is an incredible opportunity to build a new team from the ground up,&quot; Barker said from Bermuda where he and team general manager Kazuhiko &quot;Fuku&quot; Sofuku have been meeting with America's Cup officials.</p> <p>&quot;It's an honour to take on the responsibility of both CEO and skipper of SoftBank Team Japan.</p> <p>&quot;We're filling the key roles on the team as quickly as we can. I think we're pulling together a very strong team. We want to compete at the head of the fleet and we're assembling a team that is capable of doing that. Our goal is to win the America's Cup.&quot;</p> <p><b>READ MORE: <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/other-sports/68724418/more-sponsorship-money-rolls-in-for-team-new-zealand\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">More money for TNZ as sponsor signs on</a></b></p> <p>Team Japan was confirmed as a late challenger earlier this month.</p> <p>The team faces a massive challenge to make the first America's Cup world series event in Portsmouth, England, in July.</p> <p>Barker's vast experience of 20 years in the game will be crucial both on and off the water.</p> <p>&quot;In the short term, our job is to be ready to compete in Portsmouth,&quot; said Fuku.</p> <p>&quot;Then, our focus will shift to trialling more Japanese sailors as we continue to build and develop our team.&quot;</p> <p>Barker was adamant he still had an effective role to play on the water in America's Cup racing after Team New Zealand tried to move him sideways into a coaching position as Peter Burling and Glenn Ashby were named to contest the helm for Team New Zealand's next challenge.</p> <p>The 43-year-old was touted as a likely inclusion when Team Japan announced their intentions, though his name was missing from their original confirmation of entry.</p> <p>The syndicate are backed by banker Masoyashi Son whose wealth is estimated to be US$22 billion (NZ$29b), making him Japan's wealthiest man.</p> <p>Barker has surely earned himself a lucrative contract though he will have to work hard to earn his money in a rookie syndicate.</p> <p>Japan have contested three America's Cups – in 1992, 1995 and 2000 – but have no history in the new multi-hull game.</p> <p>Barker brings plenty of knowledge with him to a syndicate who are desperate to be competitive.</p> <p>He built up an intimate knowledge of the secrets that have made Team New Zealand the most consistent team in modern America's Cup history.</p> <p>With the next Cup in 2017 being raced in smaller 48-foot foiling catamarans that feature several one-design elements in key area, there is an ability for teams to get up top speed more quickly.</p> <p>Cup holder Oracle have already offered a helping hand to the Japanese with some basic design information.</p> <p>Barker's inclusion with Team Japan continues New Zealand's strong links in cup racing with that country.</p> <p>Kiwi Chris Dickson skippered Japan's 1992 challenge in San Diego where they reached the semifinals of the Louis Vuitton Cup.</p> <p>At the 1995 regatta in San Diego, New Zealander John Cutler was at the helm of the Japanese challenge that also ended at the semifinal stage.</p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815627,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T141645+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:16 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"SoftBank Team Japan\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Dean Barker wears his Team Japan colours after being announced as skipper and CEO of their America's Cup challenge for the 35th edition in 2017.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815627,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174605/627/11815627.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815628,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T141645+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:16 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"SoftBank Team Japan\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Dean Barker wears his Team Japan colours after being announced as skipper and CEO of their America's Cup challenge for the 35th edition in 2017.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815628,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174605/628/11815628.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"620\",\n                            \"height\": \"349\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815629,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T141645+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:16 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"SoftBank Team Japan\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Dean Barker wears his Team Japan colours after being announced as skipper and CEO of their America's Cup challenge for the 35th edition in 2017.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815629,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174605/629/11815629.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"200\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815630,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174605/630/11815630.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815631,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T141646+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:16 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"SoftBank Team Japan\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Dean Barker wears his Team Japan colours after being announced as skipper and CEO of their America's Cup challenge for the 35th edition in 2017.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815631,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174606/631/11815631.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"220\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815632,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T141646+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:16 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"SoftBank Team Japan\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Dean Barker wears his Team Japan colours after being announced as skipper and CEO of their America's Cup challenge for the 35th edition in 2017.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815632,\n                            \"layout\": \"ipad section splash 956:956\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174606/632/11815632.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"956\",\n                            \"height\": \"956\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68741623,\n            \"path\": \"/business/world/68741623/The-24-minute-24b-wipeout-that-halved-Chinese-billionaires-fortune\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/business/world/68741623/The-24-minute-24b-wipeout-that-halved-Chinese-billionaires-fortune\",\n            \"section\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"section-home\": \"World\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Business\",\n            \"layout\": \"landscape-image\",\n            \"title\": \"The 24-minute, $24b wipeout that halved Chinese billionaire's fortune\",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"24 minutes halved billionaire's fortune\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T141105+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"14:11 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": null,\n            \"category_id\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"stream_id\": \"stuff/business/world/68741623\",\n            \"intro\": \"Where's Li Hejun?\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"Li Hejun began the day as China's second-richest man but was almost $US14 billion poorer by 11am.\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>Where's Li Hejun?</p> <p>That's the question many were wondering when the founder, chairman and principle owner of Hanergy Thin Film Power Group failed to show up at his company's annual meeting Wednesday –&nbsp;the same day the company's stock price tanked 47 per cent, wiping out US$19 billion ($26 billion) in market value in 24 minutes.</p> <p>The entrepreneur, who began the day as China's second-richest man worth more than US$30 billion, was almost US$14 billion poorer by 11am, according to a Forbes magazine estimate.<br /> <br /> Li Hejun's absence at the shareholder meeting was all the more noteworthy because over the past year he has tirelessly championed his vision of a new era of mobile energy: thin, flexible solar cells. They would soon, he promised, be plastered on just about everything: cars, backpacks, phones, tents, satellites, flashlights, buildings, lamps, drones and clothing.<br /> <br /> Under his stewardship, the company's stock had surged more than sixfold in the past year, making it the world's most valuable solar company worth more than HK$300 billion (NZ$52.8 billion). That's larger than tech-giant Sony and seven times the size of First Solar, the biggest US solar manufacturer.</p> <p>Then on Wednesday, trading was suspended after the shares spectacularly plunged amid speculation of market manipulation and questions about the viability of the company's core technology - while the entrepreneur himself spent the morning at the opening of a clean energy exhibition in Beijing, according to a company spokesman.</p> <p>&quot;All directors of listed companies take part in setting the dates of their shareholder meetings, and they should attend,&quot; said David Webb, shareholder activist and founder of Webb-site.com.</p> <p>&quot;If a chairman of a mainland company did not show up in Hong Kong for the AGM, then it raises questions.&quot;</p> <h3>UNPROVEN TECHNOLOGY</h3> <p>&quot;The bulk of Hanergy's technology portfolio remains unproven,&quot; said Jenny Chase, lead solar industry analyst at Bloomberg New Energy Finance.</p> <p>In a six-page examination of the Hong Kong manufacturer's operations, the London-based researcher said it's been unable to find a detailed list of solar-power projects that would help explain why the company's shares surged in the past year.</p> <p>Technology aside, for months analysts and investors have raised questions about the company's revenue source: more than 60 per cent of Hanergy Thin Film's sales come from Beijing-based parent Hanergy Holding Group, a solar panel and hydroelectric company. And Hong Kong's Securities and Futures Commission has been probing market manipulation in Hanergy's shares for several weeks, according to a Reuters report. A spokesman for the regulator declined to comment.</p> <p>&quot;It's an adjustment that the market has been waiting for to happen, as Hanergy's earnings and business performance didn't support such a high stock price or valuation,&quot; said Gong Siwen, an analyst in China for Northeast Securities.</p> <p>An even more fundamental investor concern, though, is whether the company's technology actually works and how big the market for it would be.</p> <h3>AMBITIOUS PLANS</h3> <p>Li had big plans. Among them, Hanergy Thin Film has said it will begin commercially producing by October cars that will be totally powered by the sun. The vehicles would be able to drive 80 kilometres to 100 kilometres on a four-hour charge from six square metres of thin film. Yet the industry is full of examples of companies that have developed the kind of thin-film solar cells Hanergy is banking on, yet have ended up in bankruptcy.</p> <p>In an interview in March, Li called the company's investments cautious and said the earlier run-up in the stock was validation of the solar-maker's focus on a new era of mobile energy.</p> <p>No one would argue that the technology lacks promise. Because its thin-film cells can be flexible, they've found their way into applications such as the solar panels for satellites developed by NASA, backpacks and windows. Solar calculators were some of the first devices to use them. Mass production, however, has proven costly. One early flop: Solyndra went bankrupt in 2011 after getting US$528 million from the US government.</p> <p>Hanergy said in April it would build a factory to make the world's most efficient solar cells, using gallium arsenide that capture more energy from the sun. But experts cautioned that technology is years away from gaining mass appeal for the only solar market that really counts today: rooftop and utility-scale installations, an established US$24 billion market.</p> <h3>PIECEMEAL TECHNOLOGY</h3> <p>That left the company's fortunes entirely dependent on an as yet unproven technology which it has acquired piecemeal through acquisitions. Hanergy entered thin film through a buying spree. The first purchase was Solibro, a subsidiary of Germany's Q-Cells SE. That was followed by MiaSole, a California-based manufacturer, Global Solar Energy based in Arizona, and Alta Devices.</p> <p>It was the Alta purchase, completed in August 2014, that gave Hanergy a toehold in gallium arsenide. Hanergy vowed to use Alta's products in a broad range of consumer products such as mobile phones and in automobiles.</p> <p>&quot;The advantage is going to be where things have to be flexible and light,&quot; said Isik Kizilyalli, a former Alta senior scientist. &quot;I think that's where the value of what Alta will end up being until they can bring the price down,&quot; said Kizilyalli, who is the founder and chief technology officer at Avogy, an energy-efficiency electronics company.</p> <h3>CATERING TRUCKS</h3> <p>In April, Hanergy's Li unveiled partnerships to develop catering trucks and recreational vehicles that would draw on the solar-maker's panels for energy.</p> <p>The catering vehicles would generate 6 kilowatt-hours of electricity in normal sunlight for electronics such as light and refrigeration. The touring vehicle would use six 75-watt panels from MiaSole to generate 2 kilowatt-hours a day of electricity in normal light.</p> <p>BNEF's Chase wrote in a March report that she was &quot;skeptical that any thin-film technology unproven in bulk production will revolutionise the solar industry.</p> <p>&quot;While technological black swans can never be ruled out, the history of thin film has largely been one of losses and disappointments,&quot; she wrote.</p> <p>History may be proving her right.</p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816849,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T155246+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:52 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Getty\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Li has been outspoken in defending the company, saying critics fail to understand his strategy and the potential of the thin-film market.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816849,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432180366/849/11816849.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"59\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816850,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T155246+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:52 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Getty\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Li has been outspoken in defending the company, saying critics fail to understand his strategy and the potential of the thin-film market.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816850,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432180366/850/11816850.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"620\",\n                            \"height\": \"349\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816851,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T155247+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:52 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Getty\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Li has been outspoken in defending the company, saying critics fail to understand his strategy and the potential of the thin-film market.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816851,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432180367/851/11816851.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"200\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816852,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432180367/852/11816852.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816853,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T155247+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:52 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Getty\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Li has been outspoken in defending the company, saying critics fail to understand his strategy and the potential of the thin-film market.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816853,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432180367/853/11816853.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"219\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816854,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T155247+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:52 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": null,\n                    \"caption\": \" \",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816854,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432180367/854/11816854.png\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"620\",\n                            \"height\": \"348\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68693821,\n            \"path\": \"/dominion-post/68693821/Emotional-ceremony-for-Sir-Ian-Athfields-family\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/dominion-post/68693821/Emotional-ceremony-for-Sir-Ian-Athfields-family\",\n            \"section\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"section-home\": \"Dominion Post\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Dominion Post\",\n            \"layout\": \"landscape-image\",\n            \"title\": \"Emotional ceremony for Sir Ian Athfield's family\",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"Emotional ceremony for Athfield family\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T140905+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"14:09 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": \"CHLOE WINTER\",\n            \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n            \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"category_id\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"stream_id\": \"stuff/dominion-post/68693821\",\n            \"intro\": \"Architect Sir Ian Athfieldturned down three knighthoods before finally accepting one, just months before he died, his widow has revealed.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"Architect's widow accepts his knighthood, and says he turned down three previous offers.\\n\",\n            \"body\": \"<p> Architect Sir Ian Athfieldturned down three knighthoods before finally accepting one, just months before he died, his widow has revealed.</p> <p>Lady Clare Athfield, who accepted her husband's knighthood from Governor-General Sir Jerry Mateparae at Government House on Thursday, said he turned down the earlier offers because he was a humble man.</p> <p>&quot;But when he finally accepted, he started calling himself 'Sir Ath' and I had to stop saying to him, when I was in a bad mood, Sir Charles, would you mind?&quot; she laughed. His middle name was Charles.</p> <p>&quot;But he really should have been here to accept this,&quot; she said.</p> <p>Athfield died in Wellington Hospital in January, after complications from cancer surgery, but knew of his knighthood before he died.</p> <p>His widow was supported at the ceremony by their two sons, Zachary and Jesse, Zachary's wife Sarah, their children Tommy and Isla, as well as Athfield's brother, Tony, who all spoke of his great achievements.</p> <p>The ceremony brought back many memories for the family. &quot;It's very special and very emotional for all of us,&quot; Clare Athfield said.</p> <p>&quot;He's still with us everywhere, though, he hasn't gone away. He pops up in every tree, his spirit is everywhere, he is alive.&quot;</p> <p>He would live on forever in his art, she said. &quot;I don't think we've seen the end of it. What he and other creative people have achieved, it just grows with time. So we are all very lucky and very proud.&quot;</p> <p>Tony Athfield remembered a discussion about his brother's knighthood earlier this year: &quot;I asked him, how does Clare feel about being Lady Clare and he said 'She prefers to be Maid Clare'.</p> <p>&quot;He was a good brother. He was very much into architecture from a young age and he always supported me.&quot;</p> <p>Zachary Athfield said: &quot;He was a compassionate guy, a nice guy ... he started quite a lot of things that will carry on for a while, that will live on.&quot;</p> <p>In a professional career spanning half a century, his stamp was imprinted across Wellington, and with Roger Walker, he was probably New Zealand's leading exponent of modernist architecture.</p> <p>His best-known works included the Wellington City Library and its nikau palm columns, built as part of the Civic Square redevelopment in the 1980s; his own sprawling Khandallah house; the conservation of Government House; the Adam Art Gallery; and later the Clyde Quay Wharf apartments.</p> <p>He also designed Jade Stadium in Christchurch, which was da4maged in the February 2011 earthquake.</p> <p>His body of work included more than 150 projects and won him more than 60 awards.</p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815535,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T140944+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:09 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"MAARTEN HOLL/FAIRFAX NZ\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-dominion-post\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Dominion Post\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Lady Clare Athfield accepts her husband's knighthood from the Governor-General Sir Jerry Mateparae at Government House on Thursday.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815535,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174184/535/11815535.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815536,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T140944+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:09 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"MAARTEN HOLL/FAIRFAX NZ\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-dominion-post\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Dominion Post\",\n                    \"caption\": \"The late Sir Ian Athfield's son, Zachary, left, wife Lady Clare, son Jesse, and brother Tony with the insignia of his knighthood.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815536,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174184/536/11815536.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"620\",\n                            \"height\": \"349\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815537,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T140944+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:09 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"MAARTEN HOLL/FAIRFAX NZ\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-dominion-post\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Dominion Post\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Lady Clare Athfield accepts her husband's knighthood from the Governor-General Sir Jerry Mateparae at Government House on Thursday.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815537,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174184/537/11815537.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"238\",\n                            \"height\": \"286\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815538,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T140944+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:09 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"MAARTEN HOLL/FAIRFAX NZ\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-dominion-post\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Dominion Post\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Lady Clare Athfield accepts her husband's knighthood from the Governor-General Sir Jerry Mateparae at Government House on Thursday.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815538,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174184/538/11815538.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"200\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815539,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174184/539/11815539.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815540,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T140944+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:09 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"MAARTEN HOLL/FAIRFAX NZ\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-dominion-post\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Dominion Post\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Lady Clare Athfield accepts her husband's knighthood from the Governor-General Sir Jerry Mateparae at Government House on Thursday.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815540,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174184/540/11815540.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"220\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815541,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T140944+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:09 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"MAARTEN HOLL/FAIRFAX NZ\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-dominion-post\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Dominion Post\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Lady Clare Athfield accepts her husband's knighthood from the Governor-General Sir Jerry Mateparae at Government House on Thursday.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815541,\n                            \"layout\": \"ipad section splash 956:956\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432174184/541/11815541.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"956\",\n                            \"height\": \"956\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68742199,\n            \"path\": \"/business/68742199/Budget-2015-Benefits-rise-in-bid-to-tackle-child-poverty\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/business/68742199/Budget-2015-Benefits-rise-in-bid-to-tackle-child-poverty\",\n            \"section\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"section-home\": \"Business\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Business\",\n            \"layout\": \"a-standard\",\n            \"title\": \"Budget 2015: Benefits rise in bid to tackle child poverty\",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"Benefits rise in bid to tackle child poverty\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T140836+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"14:08 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": \"STACEY KIRK\",\n            \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n            \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"intro\": \"A $790 million package to lift children out of poverty will see benefits rise beyond inflation for the first time in 30 years, but it won't come for free.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"A $790 million package to lift children out of poverty will see benefits rise beyond inflation for the first time in 30 years, but it won't come for free.\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>A $790 million package to lift children out of poverty will see benefits rise beyond inflation for the first time in 30 years, but it won't come for free.</p> <p>The Government also imposing stricter work obligations.</p> <p>The package, announced in the Governnment's Budget on Thursday, will give families on benefits with children a $25-a-week boost to their incomes, while-low income working families will get at least $12.50 a week extra.</p> <p>The increase to benefits is the first, beyond inflation, since 1977.</p> <p>A <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/68600911/income-inequality-how-nz-is-one-of-the-worst-in-the-world\\\">Stuff.co.nz data project</a> highlighted the disparity between rises to superannuation compared with those in the most in the severe hardship since 2007.</p> <p><b>READ MORE: <br /> * <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/68729413/budget-2015-tackling-hardship-with-an-eye-to-future-tax-cuts\\\">Budget 2015: Benefits rise in bid to tackle child poverty<br /> </a>*&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/68600911/income-inequality-how-nz-is-one-of-the-worst-in-the-world\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Our inequality story: Why New Zealand is one of the worst in the world<br /> </a>*&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/68736405/budget-live-stream.html\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">LIVE: Watch the Budget speech and debate in Parliament</a><br /> * <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/budget-2015.html\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Full coverage</a><br /> *&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/68741678/\\\">Modest tax cuts for 2017</a></b></p> <p>Thursday's package is expected to affect about 110,000 families, with 190,000 children, living in the most severe hardship.</p> <p>But the Government has made it clear it expects more people working more hours, while it searches for ways to boost a lower-than-forecast tax revenue.</p> <p>Most significantly, sole parents on a benefit will be forced to return to part-time work two years earlier, when their child turns three.</p> <p>However, those parents would be eligible for increased childcare assistance.</p> <p>Increased work obligations would apply to all beneficiaries - the main changes include:</p> <p>* Most sole-parents, and partners of beneficiaries, will have to be available for part-time work once their youngest child turns three, rather than the current age of five.</p> <p>* All beneficiaries with part-time work obligations would be expected to find work for 20 hours a week, rather than current 15 hours.</p> <p>* Benefit rates for families with children will raise by $25 a week after tax - the first time since 1972 that core benefits rates have been increased by more than inflation.</p> <p>* Beneficiaries receiving Sole Parent Support will have to reapply for their benefit every year.</p> <p>* Low-income working families earning $36,350 a year or less, before tax, will get $12.50 extra a week from Working for Families.</p> <p>* Some very low-income working families will get $24.50 extra per week.</p> <p>* Higher income families earning more than $88,000 a year would get slightly less from Working for Families - losing about &nbsp;$3 a week from their pay packets.</p> <p>Social Development Minister Anne Tolley said she was confident the package would not contribute to further welfare dependency, but would have a &quot;positive impact&quot; on New Zealand's poorest families.</p> <p>&quot;While two-thirds of children in more severe material hardship live in beneficiary families, the remaining third have working parents on low incomes, and the Government thinks those families could also do with extra support,&quot; she said.</p> <p>The Government was expecting the package to have a &quot;meaningful impact&quot; on four different groups of families in New Zealand.</p> <p>They were beneficiary families, low and very low-income working families as well as well as families earning more than $36,350 a year.</p> <p><b>WHAT THIS MEANS FOR FAMILIES:</b></p> <p>* Low income families will be eligible for a higher rate of Childcare Assistance for pre-school and out-of-school care, with the rate increasing from $4 per hour to $5 per hour.</p> <p>* Working families earning less than $27,000 per year in gross income will get the full $12.50 a week extra, from the in-work tax credit, plus $12 a week from the minimum family tax credit - a total increase of $24.50 per week.</p> <p>* Other working families earning $36,350 or less a year will get the full $12.50 a week extra, from the rise to the in-work tax credit.</p> <p>* Working families earning more than $36,350 will get progressively smaller increases as their incomes get higher - a family earning $45,000, for example, would get an increase of $10.42 a week.</p> <p>* Some families will get less than they did before, from Working for Families, most of those being higher income earners on more than $88,000 a year.</p> <p>* Main benefit rates for all families with children will increase $25 per week. The main benefits are the Supported Living Payment, for people unable to work due to illness or disability; Sole Parent Support, for sole parents with children under 14, Jobseeker Support and the Emergency Benefit, for people in hardship who don't qualify for the other types of benefit.</p> <p>* About nine in 10 of those families are sole parent families. The increase amounts to an 8.3 per cent increase in most sole parents' base rate of benefit (currently $301 a week).</p> <p>*&nbsp; Student Allowance rates for families with children will also increase by $25 a week.</p> <p><b>THE CRITERIA:</b></p> <p>* Beneficiaries receiving sole parent support will have to reapply for the benefit every year. This is expected to affect about 70,000 sole parents.</p> <p>* Those on Jobseeker support already have to reapply for their benefits every year.</p> <p>* Benefit families who pay income-related rents for social housing will pay slightly more. Their rent is set at 25 per cent of their income, so with a $25-per-week boost their rent would rise by $6.25 a week.</p> <p>* From April 1, next year sole parents will be required to go into part-time work when their youngest child turns three.</p> <p>* Part-time work is now considered a minimum of 20 hours, rather than the current 15.&nbsp;</p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816025,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T144542+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:45 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Brad Calkins 123RF\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Stock Photo - Coin piles compound interest banking, coins, compound, interest, money, piles, save, savings, stacks generic\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816025,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432176342/025/11816025.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816026,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T144542+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:45 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Brad Calkins 123RF\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Stock Photo - Coin piles compound interest banking, coins, compound, interest, money, piles, save, savings, stacks generic\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816026,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432176342/026/11816026.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"200\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816027,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432176342/027/11816027.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816028,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T144542+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:45 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Brad Calkins 123RF\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Stock Photo - Coin piles compound interest banking, coins, compound, interest, money, piles, save, savings, stacks generic\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816028,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432176342/028/11816028.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"220\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68702774,\n            \"path\": \"/business/68702774/Budget-2015-Education-whats-in-it-for-schools\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/business/68702774/Budget-2015-Education-whats-in-it-for-schools\",\n            \"section\": \"National\",\n            \"section-home\": \"Business\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Business\",\n            \"layout\": \"landscape-video\",\n            \"title\": \"Budget 2015: Education - what's in it for schools? \",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"Spending on special needs\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T140657+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"14:06 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": \"JO MOIR\",\n            \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n            \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"category_id\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"stream_id\": \"stuff/business/68702774\",\n            \"intro\": \"The Government has answered schools' cries for more cash at their disposal and extra help for special needs children.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"Government answers schools' cries for more cash and help for special needs kids.\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>The Government has answered schools' cries for more cash at their disposal and extra help for special needs children.</p> <p>The Budget will inject $62.9 million over four years into special education that will provide an extra 500 students with Ongoing Resource Scheme (ORS) support, which brings the total number of special needs children being supported to 9000.</p> <p>It pays for specialists such as speech-language therapists, psychologists, physiotherapists and occupational therapists, and provides additional teacher and teacher's aide time.</p> <p><b>READ MORE:</b></p> <p><b>* <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/68729413/budget-2015-tackling-hardship-with-an-eye-to-future-tax-cuts\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Tackling hardship&nbsp;</a></b></p> <p><b>* <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/budget-2015.html\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Full Budget coverage</a></b></p> <p><b>* <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/68741678/budget-2015-modest-tax-cuts-flagged-for-2017\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Modest tax cuts flagged</a></b></p> <p>The Budget also includes new spending for extra in-class teacher's aide support, which is designed to help those students with special needs that don't meet the requirements for ORS funding, for example, children with dyslexia, autism, ADHD and foetal alcohol spectrum disorder.&nbsp;</p> <p>&quot;This is the first phase of our commitment to provide extra teacher's aide support for an extra 4000 students,&quot; Education Minister Hekia Parata said.</p> <p>&quot;Eventually we aim to provide an additional 800,000 teacher's aide hours a year.&quot;</p> <p>The splash on special needs comes on the back of an underspend of more than $32m of special needs funding in the last two years, which enraged schools and parents.</p> <p>A delay between announcing special education programmes and implementing them - a &quot;usual practice&quot; by the Ministry of Education - was responsible for the underspend.</p> <p><b>READ MORE: <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/67753483/Government-underspend-punishes-schools\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Special needs underspend punishes schools</a></b></p> <p>Principals repeatedly calling for more in their operations funding to meet the true cost of education will welcome an increase, albeit a small one at only 1 per cent at a cost of $42.3m to the Government.</p> <p>&quot;This new funding, along with new funding for roll growth, will bring the total amount spent on school operational grants to $1.32 billion during 2015/16,&quot; Parata said.</p> <p>But it's not only state schools getting a helping hand - controversial charter schools will continue to grow with funding being put aside to establish two new charter schools, which are expected to open in either 2016 or 2017.</p> <p>There are already nine charter schools operating, most in Auckland and Northland. But with one of the schools, Whangaruru, on the verge of closure, the model has been heavily criticised.</p> <p><b>READ MORE: <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/education/66444892/Parata-puts-charter-school-on-final-notice\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Minister gives Whangaruru final warning</a></b></p> <p>Roll numbers at the schools are yet to hit targets and Parata is expected to make a decision on the closure of Whangaruru soon after poor teaching practice, student attendance and management were highlighted in an Education Review Office report.</p> <p>The 2015 Budget investment of $686.7m will take total spending on early childhood, primary and secondary education in the coming year to $10.8 billion.</p> <p>A large chunk of that - $244m - was announced pre-budget to pay for the building of seven new schools and kura kaupapa, expanding four existing schools and building an additional 241 classrooms at existing schools.</p> <p>Other investment includes $74.9m for early childhood education to ensure more children are attending for longer hours.</p> <p>There is also an additional $53.3m being spent to continue to fix the botched payroll system, Novopay.</p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816907,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T155714+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:57 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": null,\n                    \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Finance Minister Bill English delivers the Budget 2015 announcing an changes to Kiwi Saver, benefits and border security.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816907,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432180634/907/11816907.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816908,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T155714+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:57 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Bruce Mercer\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"waikato-times\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Waikato Times\",\n                    \"caption\": \"\\\"This is the first phase of our commitment to provide extra teacher's aide support for an extra 4000 students,\\\" Education Minister Hekia Parata said.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816908,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432180634/908/11816908.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"59\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816909,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T155714+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:57 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Bruce Mercer\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"waikato-times\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Waikato Times\",\n                    \"caption\": \"\\\"This is the first phase of our commitment to provide extra teacher's aide support for an extra 4000 students,\\\" Education Minister Hekia Parata said.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816909,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432180634/909/11816909.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"620\",\n                            \"height\": \"348\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816910,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T155714+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:57 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Bruce Mercer\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"waikato-times\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Waikato Times\",\n                    \"caption\": \"\\\"This is the first phase of our commitment to provide extra teacher's aide support for an extra 4000 students,\\\" Education Minister Hekia Parata said.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816910,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432180634/910/11816910.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"200\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816911,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432180634/911/11816911.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816912,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T155714+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:57 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Bruce Mercer\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"waikato-times\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Waikato Times\",\n                    \"caption\": \"\\\"This is the first phase of our commitment to provide extra teacher's aide support for an extra 4000 students,\\\" Education Minister Hekia Parata said.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816912,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432180634/912/11816912.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"219\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ],\n            \"videos\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816395,\n                    \"layout\": \"Standard Video\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"aap\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"AAP\",\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T151532+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:15 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Parliament TV\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Finance Minister Bill English delivers the Budget 2015 announcing an changes to Kiwi Saver, benefits and border security.\",\n                    \"src\": \"http://file2.stuff.co.nz/1432178132/396/11816396.mp4\",\n                    \"video_poster\": {\n                        \"id\": 11816397,\n                        \"layout\": \"Video Image\",\n                        \"src\": \"http://file2.stuff.co.nz/1432180634/397/11816397.jpg\",\n                        \"width\": \"640\",\n                        \"height\": \"360\"\n                    }\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68702439,\n            \"path\": \"/business/68702439/Budget-2015-Budget-keeps-to-the-small-and-narrow\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/business/68702439/Budget-2015-Budget-keeps-to-the-small-and-narrow\",\n            \"section\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"section-home\": \"Business\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Business\",\n            \"layout\": \"landscape-image\",\n            \"title\": \"Budget 2015: Budget keeps to the small and narrow\",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"Surplus gone but not forgotten\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T140041+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"14:00 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": \"VERNON SMALL\",\n            \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n            \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"category_id\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"stream_id\": \"stuff/business/68702439\",\n            \"intro\": \"Finance Minister Bill English has called it a responsible and supportive Budget, but a better description might be small and narrow. \",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"Bill English calls the Budget responsible, but it's also small and narrow. \\n\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>Finance Minister Bill English has called it a responsible and supportive Budget, but a better description might be small and narrow.&nbsp;</p> <p>A little Budget (but not in a Labour leader way) that goes for the surplus forecast too.</p> <p>It's the sort of document you ought to expect from a re-elected government, especially one that has a slim $1 billion a year for new initiatives and is keeping its fiscal powder dry for a modest tax cut in election year - 2017.</p> <p>There are some winners, but also some tweaks that rake in more revenue. Yet overall there are no economically significant new moves, though there are some nuanced political ones.</p> <p><b>READ MORE:</b></p> <p><b>*&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/68729413/budget-2015-tackling-hardship-with-an-eye-to-future-tax-cuts\\\">Tackling hardship with an eye to future tax cuts</a></b></p> <p><b>*&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/budget-2015.html\\\">Full Budget coverage</a></b></p> <p>The most obvious is a sizable $240 million a year nod towards beneficiary parents with children, who have become a cause celebre for social equity groups because they have been denied the tax credit available to those in work.&nbsp;</p> <p>At the same time Working for Families payments at the lower income levels rise to help preserve the gap between benefits and work.</p> <p>At the same time beneficiaries will have to be available for work when their child turns three years old, down from five now, and the part-time work requirement rises from 15 to 20 hours.</p> <p>Arriving or leaving the country will also cost you in future via a new levy at the border.&nbsp;</p> <p>The Government will also make a big saving by immediately canning the $1000 KiwiSaver kickstart - continuing its theme of slowly stripping the incentives from the former Labour government's scheme.</p> <p>Together those two measures will save the Government about $225m a year - which, given the state of the Budget balance, will be handy chump change.</p> <p>Ah, the surplus, the surplus. Gone but not forgotten.&nbsp;</p> <p>The books are forecast to be in deficit by $684m this year, improving to an anaemic surplus of $176m next year. That is well within the danger zone for English to report an eighth straight year in the red.</p> <p>And there are risks around that too.&nbsp;</p> <p>Dairy prices are softening and our main trading partners' growth is slowing.&nbsp;</p> <p>There is also an apparently heroic forecast of unemployment falling from 5.8 per cent now to less than 5 per cent during 2016 - even though growth slides from 3.3 per cent this year to under 3 per cent by the next election.</p> <p>The biggest disappointment, given the pre-Budget billing, was the slim $52.2m being made available &quot;to facilitate housing development on Crown-owned land in Auckland&quot;.&nbsp;</p> <p>For all the talk of swaths of government-owned land, it doesn't sound like a lot of land or a lot of houses at current Auckland prices.</p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815769,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T142753+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:27 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Ross Giblin\",\n                    \"caption\": \"The 2015 Budget.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815769,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432175273/769/11815769.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815770,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T142753+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:27 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Getty Images\",\n                    \"caption\": \"It's the sort of document you ought to expect from a re-elected government.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815770,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432175273/770/11815770.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"620\",\n                            \"height\": \"349\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815771,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T142753+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:27 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Ross Giblin\",\n                    \"caption\": \"The 2015 Budget.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815771,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432175273/771/11815771.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"200\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815772,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432175273/772/11815772.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815773,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T142753+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:27 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Ross Giblin\",\n                    \"caption\": \"The 2015 Budget.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815773,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432175273/773/11815773.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"220\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68702261,\n            \"path\": \"/business/68702261/Budget-2015-National-makes-some-concessions-but-also-gets-tough\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/business/68702261/Budget-2015-National-makes-some-concessions-but-also-gets-tough\",\n            \"section\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"section-home\": \"Business\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Business\",\n            \"layout\": \"landscape-image\",\n            \"title\": \"Budget 2015: National makes some concessions but also gets tough\",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"The carrot and stick Budget\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T140000+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"14:00 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": \"TRACY WATKINS\",\n            \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n            \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"intro\": \"This Budget has Bill English's name on it and John Key's fist print plastered all over it.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"This Budget has English’s name on it and Key’s fist print all over it.\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>This Budget has Bill English's name on it and John Key's fist print plastered all over it.</p> <p>Boosting benefits for the first time in 43 years is a big concession from a National government, even one that has spent the last seven years firmly focused on shedding the flinty face it carried over the 1990s, and in particular from Ruth Richardson's Mother of all Budgets and 1991 benefit cuts.</p> <p>But it is also a measure of the importance the Key government places on retaining the crucial female vote and a necessary prerequisite to cutting taxes in two years' time, which Thursday's Budget reiterates as a priority ahead of seeking a fourth term.</p> <p><b>READ MORE:</b></p> <p><b>* <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/budget-2015.html\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Full Budget coverage</a></b></p> <p><b>* <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/68741678/budget-2015-modest-tax-cuts-flagged-for-2017\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Modest tax cuts flagged</a></b></p> <p><b>* <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/68742541/budget-2015-health-gets-billiondollar-shot-in-the-arm\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Health gets billion-dollar shot in the arm</a></b></p> <p>Tax cuts disproportionately benefiting the better off would have been politically unsellable after Key went into the last election promising to make child poverty and hardship his priority.</p> <p>In a typically carrot and stick approach from National, Thursday's benefit increase is accompanied by much tougher work obligations for teen mums and jobless mums and dads, including a requirement to be ready for work once their youngest child turns three, not five as now.&nbsp;</p> <p>That will make it easier to sell among working families in middle New Zealand who will get proportionately less from working for families benefit increases.&nbsp;</p> <p>There will be some fallout over axing the KiwiSaver kickstart payment of $1000, but that will be limited by the fact that most eligible people have already signed up.</p> <p>Politically, this is one of the smartest Budgets yet from Key and English - and that is a high accolade for a Government that has consistently snookered its opponents by surprising on the upside with measures like last year's extension of free doctors' visits to children under 13.</p> <p>The biggest howls of outrage will more likely come from National's base and from the political right, rather than from the left.</p> <p>There will be concern in particular that after failing to hit its target of returning to surplus this year the target for next year looks just as marginal.</p> <p>Complaints about that will be muted for now especially with the prospect of tax cuts being dangled in front of voters for 2017 or 2018.</p> <p>But they will get a lot louder if this year's Budget means next year's surplus falls by the wayside again.</p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815837,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T143155+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:31 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"David White/Fairfax NZ\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Politically, this is one of the smartest Budgets yet from Prime Minister John Key and Finance Minister Bill English - and that is a high accolade.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815837,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432175515/837/11815837.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"59\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815838,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T143155+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:31 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"David White/Fairfax NZ\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Politically, this is one of the smartest Budgets yet from Prime Minister John Key and Finance Minister Bill English - and that is a high accolade.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815838,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432175515/838/11815838.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"620\",\n                            \"height\": \"348\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815839,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T143156+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:31 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"David White/Fairfax NZ\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Politically, this is one of the smartest Budgets yet from Prime Minister John Key and Finance Minister Bill English - and that is a high accolade.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815839,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432175516/839/11815839.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"199\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815840,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432175516/840/11815840.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815841,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T143156+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:31 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"David White/Fairfax NZ\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Politically, this is one of the smartest Budgets yet from Prime Minister John Key and Finance Minister Bill English - and that is a high accolade.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815841,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432175516/841/11815841.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"219\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68731784,\n            \"path\": \"/entertainment/celebrities/68731784/Johnny-Depp-departs-Australia-leaving-Pirates-of-the-Caribbean-5-in-the-lurch\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/entertainment/celebrities/68731784/Johnny-Depp-departs-Australia-leaving-Pirates-of-the-Caribbean-5-in-the-lurch\",\n            \"section\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"section-home\": \"Celebrities\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Entertainment\",\n            \"layout\": \"landscape-video\",\n            \"title\": \"Johnny Depp departs Australia, leaving Pirates of the Caribbean 5 in the lurch\",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"Johnny Depp walks off Pirates set \",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T135317+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"13:53 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": null,\n            \"source_code\": \"aap\",\n            \"source_name\": \"AAP\",\n            \"intro\": \"Johnny Depp is set to leave Australia in the coming days, but the publicist for the Pirates of the Caribbean says there is no truth to reports he is fleeing to resurrect his marriage.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"Johnny Depp's publicist has denied he's heading back to the United States to save his marriage to Amber Heard.\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>Johnny Depp is set to leave Australia in the coming days, but the publicist for the&nbsp;Pirates of the Caribbean&nbsp;says there is no truth to reports he is fleeing to resurrect his marriage.<br /> <br /> There has been extraordinary attention on the movements of 51-year-old Depp, who has been filming the fifth instalment of&nbsp;Pirates&nbsp;on Queensland's Gold Coast.</p> <p><b>ALSO READ:&nbsp;<br /> <br /> *<a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/celebrities/68547031/johnny-depps-dogs-on-puppy-death-row\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Johnny Depp's dogs on puppy death row<br /> </a>*<a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/celebrities/68571671/johnny-depp-and-amber-heard-to-take-dogs-boo-and-pistol-home-to-us\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Johnny Depp and Amber Heard to take dogs Boo and Pistol home to US<br /> </a>*<a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/film/67231280/Pirates-of-the-Caribbean-5-Johnny-Depp-injured-on-Gold-Coast\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Pirates of the Caribbean 5: Johnny Depp injured on Gold Coast</a></b></p> <p>News Corp reported on Thursday that Depp had walked off set and and was planning to head back to the United States because of relationship problems&nbsp;with wife Amber Heard.</p> <p>Publicist Michael Singer said the claims were untrue.</p> <p>&quot;I can't go into detail on our filming schedules or the movements of individuals but I can tell you that nothing in that report has any relation to reality,&quot; Singer said.</p> <p>&quot;Mr Depp has been filming on schedule. It's business as usual with all participants working.&quot;</p> <p><img src=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/content/dam/images/1/3/h/y/n/e/image.related.StuffLandscapeSixteenByNine.620x349.14t787.png/1431585122773.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"The fifth instalment of the Pirates franchise, Dead Men Tell No Tales is currently filming on the Gold Coast.\\\" /></p> <p>Fairfax Media understands Depp is planning to leave Australia, possibly to be with his daughter Lily-Rose Depp who turns 16 next week.</p> <p>Production sources said the break had been factored into the movie's filming schedule.</p> <p>It comes after Depp hired a charter plane to fly two of his Yorkshire terriers, Pistol and Boo, back to the US last week because they allegedly had been brought into the country illegally.</p> <p>Some US entertainment sites claim Heard had previously been asked to leave the&nbsp;Pirates&nbsp;set by producers because the couple's constant fighting was causing disruptions.</p> <p>Heard, 29, married Depp on his private island in the Bahamas in February.</p> <p><img src=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/content/dam/images/1/4/t/m/4/w/image.related.StuffLandscapeSixteenByNine.620x349.14tq8n.png/1431650692009.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"Johnny Depp with one of his beloved pooches.\\\" /></p> <p>Issues that have plagued&nbsp;<i>Pirates of the Carribean: Dead Men Tell No Tales</i>:</p> <p>- Filming is delayed because of Tropical Cyclone Nathan, the second major storm to lash Queensland in March.</p> <p>- An imposter dressed as a&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/pirate-threatens-pirates-of-the-caribbean-movie-security-police-20150310-1403im.html\\\">pirate allegedly breaks onto the set and&nbsp;threatens security with a knife</a>.</p> <p>-&nbsp;Johnny Depp injures his hand&nbsp;while staying at Mick Doohan's luxury mansion on the Gold Coast. He flies back to the US for treatment, resulting in production being halted and 200-odd staff being stood down for several weeks.</p> <p>- Production of the movie is forced to temporarily shift from the Gold Coast to Raby Bay because of rough waters.&nbsp;​</p> <p><a href=\\\"https://www.facebook.com/GossipStuff?ref=hl\\\"><b>Head to our Facebook page for more from Stuff Entertainment</b></a></p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815324,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T135343+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:53 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": null,\n                    \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Depp to leave Australia again\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815324,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432173223/324/11815324.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815325,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T135343+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:53 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Nine News\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Johnny Depp and Amber Heard at Brisbane Airport.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815325,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432173223/325/11815325.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"59\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815326,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T135343+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:53 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Nine News\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Johnny Depp and Amber Heard at Brisbane Airport.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815326,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432173223/326/11815326.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"618\",\n                            \"height\": \"349\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815327,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T135343+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:53 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Nine News\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Johnny Depp and Amber Heard at Brisbane Airport.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815327,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432173223/327/11815327.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"200\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815328,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432173223/328/11815328.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815329,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T135343+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:53 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Nine News\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Johnny Depp and Amber Heard at Brisbane Airport.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815329,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432173223/329/11815329.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"416\",\n                            \"height\": \"220\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815330,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T135343+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:53 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Nine News\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Johnny Depp and Amber Heard at Brisbane Airport.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815330,\n                            \"layout\": \"ipad section splash 956:956\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432173223/330/11815330.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"956\",\n                            \"height\": \"956\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ],\n            \"videos\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815292,\n                    \"layout\": \"Standard Video\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"aap\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"AAP\",\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T134830+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:48 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"The Brisbane Times\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Johnny Depp is again set to leave the set of Pirates of the Caribbean 5 on the Gold Coast to return home to the United States.\\r\\n\",\n                    \"src\": \"http://file2.stuff.co.nz/1432172910/293/11815293.mp4\",\n                    \"video_poster\": {\n                        \"id\": 11815295,\n                        \"layout\": \"Video Image\",\n                        \"src\": \"http://file2.stuff.co.nz/1432173223/295/11815295.jpg\",\n                        \"width\": \"640\",\n                        \"height\": \"360\"\n                    }\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68731279,\n            \"path\": \"/southland-times/news/68731279/Glenorchy-and-Te-Anau-residents-oppose-Milford-rail-project\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/southland-times/news/68731279/Glenorchy-and-Te-Anau-residents-oppose-Milford-rail-project\",\n            \"section\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"section-home\": \"News\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Southland Times\",\n            \"layout\": \"landscape-image\",\n            \"title\": \"Glenorchy and Te Anau residents oppose Milford rail project\",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"Residents oppose rail project\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T134337+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"13:43 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": \"CHE BAKER\",\n            \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n            \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"intro\": \"Glenorchy and Te Anau residents oppose a $274-million plan to build an electric railway through a tunnel to link Queenstown and Milford Sound.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"Residents prepared to fight a $274m electric railway proposal which would link Queenstown and Milford Sound.\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>Glenorchy and Te Anau residents oppose a $274-million plan to build an electric railway through a tunnel to link Queenstown and Milford Sound.</p> <p>One town does not want an influx of tourists, while the other does not want tourists&nbsp;bypassing it.</p> <p>MSLR has <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/southland-times/68700168/new-milford-sound-to-queenstown-rail-plan-mooted\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">proposed to build a 15-kilometre vehicular drive-on-drive-off electric railway,</a>&nbsp;through a 13.5km tunnel between Milford Sound and Queenstown.</p> <p>It was the third such plan to shortcut the 287km road trip, with&nbsp;Conservation Minister Nick Smith <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/8930108/Government-axes-Milford-Tunnel\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">rejecting a&nbsp;$180 million plan</a> by Milford Dart to build a tunnel through the Mt Aspiring National Park and the Fiordland Link Experience, a <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/10099108/240-million-Fiordland-monorail-rejected\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">$240 million monorail&nbsp;project</a>.</p> <p>Enviro Glenorchy, formally know as the Stop the Tunnel&nbsp;group, spokeswoman Trish Fraser said she believed Smith &quot;was clear he has shut the door&quot; on proposed plans in the area, &quot;but obviously not&quot;.</p> <p>Fraser&nbsp;said the group would be keeping the eye on the project and would be ready to fight it.</p> <p>In 2012 the group collected over <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/southland-times/news/7488204/Select-committee-for-anti-tunnel-petition\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">25,000 online signatures opposing</a> the Milford tunnel proposal which were accepted by the Local Government and Environment Select Committee.</p> <p>Fraser said the environmental impacts of the MSLR plan were unnecessary and the road from Queenstown to Glenorchy would not be able to cope with the extra traffic.</p> <p>&quot;That [the traffic impact] would be enormous. The road is already really busy with tourists,&quot; she said.</p> <p>She believed most of the town's residents would object to the proposal, as 98 per cent were against the Milford tunnel proposal.</p> <p>With foreign investors there were bound to be more schemes in the future, she said.</p> <p>However, &quot;it doesn't need to happen ... I would certainly be against it happening,&quot; she said.</p> <p>MSLR said it would run up to 12 train trips a day and each train would contain 10 single railroad low bed wagons, each capable of transporting a large tourist coach up to 12.6m and 20 tonnes in weight, and 10 regular flat bed wagons catering for up to 30 light vehicles.</p> <p>Annually, it could transport 700,000 passengers, over 3000 passengers a day</p> <p>Save Fiordland chairman Bill Jarvie, of Te Anau,&nbsp;said he believed the project would have similar environmental impacts as the failed Milford tunnel proposal.</p> <p>Jarvie, who said he was not outright opposed to development, said people travelling to the wilderness knew it took time and did not need to be rushed.</p> <p>&quot;The very thing people come to this country for (nature), they will effectively be ruining.&quot;</p> <p>If the project went ahead, it would have a negative impact on tourism in Te Anau community, he said.</p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816605,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T153501+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:35 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": null,\n                    \"caption\": \" \",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816605,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432179554/605/11816605.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"620\",\n                            \"height\": \"348\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816621,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T153913+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:39 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Barry Harcourt\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n                    \"caption\": \"A new rail tunnel has been proposed to speed up travel between Queenstown and Milford Sound.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816621,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432179553/621/11816621.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816622,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T153913+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:39 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Barry Harcourt\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n                    \"caption\": \"A new rail tunnel has been proposed to speed up travel between Queenstown and Milford Sound.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816622,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432179553/622/11816622.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"620\",\n                            \"height\": \"349\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816623,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T153914+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:39 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Barry Harcourt\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n                    \"caption\": \"A new rail tunnel has been proposed to speed up travel between Queenstown and Milford Sound.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816623,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432179554/623/11816623.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"200\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816624,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432179554/624/11816624.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11816625,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T153914+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"15:39 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Barry Harcourt\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n                    \"caption\": \"A new rail tunnel has been proposed to speed up travel between Queenstown and Milford Sound.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11816625,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432179554/625/11816625.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"220\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68702228,\n            \"path\": \"/business/better-business/68702228/Caution-urged-on-debt-collectors-after-Orcon-ordered-to-pay-25k\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/business/better-business/68702228/Caution-urged-on-debt-collectors-after-Orcon-ordered-to-pay-25k\",\n            \"section\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"section-home\": \"Better Business\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Business\",\n            \"layout\": \"a-standard\",\n            \"title\": \"Caution urged on debt collectors after Orcon ordered to pay $25k\",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"'Make debt collectors a last resort'\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T132647+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"13:26 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": \"SUSAN TEODORO\",\n            \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n            \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"intro\": \"Companies should not refer debts still under dispute to a debt collector, Privacy Commissioner John Edwards has urged.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"Companies should not refer debts still under dispute to a debt collector, the Privacy Commissioner has urged.\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>Companies should not refer debts still under dispute to a debt collector, Privacy Commissioner John Edwards has urged.</p> <p>His comments come after Orcon was ordered to pay $25,000 to a Manawatu soldier following a dispute over a $208 bill.</p> <p>&quot;If there is a debt in dispute, companies have a very high duty to check they are not in error because there can be profound consequences for the individual if they get it wrong,&quot; Edwards said on Thursday.</p> <p>&quot;Here we had a soldier with a young family who was unable to gain rental accommodation as a result of this particular failure.&quot;</p> <p>Telecommunications company Orcon were ordered to pay the Manawatu man $25,000 in damages and train its staff on how to apply the Privacy Act on Wednesday.</p> <p>The Human Rights Review Tribunal, sitting in Palmerston North, found that Orcon should not have referred a disputed bill to collection agency Baycorp.</p> <p>The telco must pay customer Brett Taylor $10,000 for negatively affecting his good credit rating and $15,000 for humiliation, loss of dignity and injury to feelings.</p> <p>&quot;In view of the seemingly complete failure by Orcon to evidence an understanding of its obligations under the information privacy principles, it is our view a training order is necessary,&quot; said the tribunal.</p> <p>Defence force employee Taylor and his partner Chloe Tasker said the referral of the bill had affected their credit rating and prevented them and their 12-month-old daughter from finding accommodation.</p> <p>The dispute started when Taylor ordered the Genius Full broadband package and a landline.</p> <p>Orcon provided the wrong modem and connection was delayed while a replacement was requested.</p> <p>After the correct modem arrived neither the broadband nor the telephone worked, despite repeated calls to the Orcon support line.</p> <p>The couple immediately cancelled the account and said they were told by Orcon that no payment was due, but they kept receiving bills and the dispute continued.</p> <p>Orcon then sent the account to debt collector Baycorp.</p> <p>Taylor said the referral of the bill to the agency had caused him and his family considerable stress, including testing his relationship and career as well as affecting his credit history.</p> <p>&quot;As a young family, we need to be able to gain credit. My credit rating also affects my position in the army, and advancements in rank. I needed peace of mind that I would not have adverse credit for five years,&quot; Taylor told the tribunal.</p> <p>Tasker said they were also declined a debt consolidation loan.</p> <p>&quot;After that call, I was really emotional,&quot; she told the tribunal.</p> <p>The tribunal said it was remarkable that even when asked by its own debt collection agency to investigate the alleged debt, the telco did nothing.&nbsp;</p> <p>Orcon declined to comment.</p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815126,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T132740+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:27 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"123RF\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Image ID : 31034652 new zealand investing generic investment\\nbanknote, buying, cash, changing, currency, dealing, dollars, exchange, hand, market, money, paying, racketeer, selling, shopping, tourist\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815126,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432171660/126/11815126.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815127,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T132740+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:27 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"123RF\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Image ID : 31034652 new zealand investing generic investment\\nbanknote, buying, cash, changing, currency, dealing, dollars, exchange, hand, market, money, paying, racketeer, selling, shopping, tourist\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815127,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432171660/127/11815127.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"200\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815128,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432171660/128/11815128.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815129,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T132740+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:27 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"123RF\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Image ID : 31034652 new zealand investing generic investment\\nbanknote, buying, cash, changing, currency, dealing, dollars, exchange, hand, market, money, paying, racketeer, selling, shopping, tourist\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815129,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432171660/129/11815129.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"220\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815130,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T132740+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:27 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"123RF\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Image ID : 31034652 new zealand investing generic investment\\nbanknote, buying, cash, changing, currency, dealing, dollars, exchange, hand, market, money, paying, racketeer, selling, shopping, tourist\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815130,\n                            \"layout\": \"ipad section splash 956:956\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432171660/130/11815130.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"956\",\n                            \"height\": \"956\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68731636,\n            \"path\": \"/national/crime/68731636/Rotorua-council-in-lockdown-after-white-powder-in-package\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/national/crime/68731636/Rotorua-council-in-lockdown-after-white-powder-in-package\",\n            \"section\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"section-home\": \"Crime\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"National\",\n            \"layout\": \"landscape-image\",\n            \"title\": \"Rotorua council in lockdown after white powder in package\",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"Lockdown after powder scare\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T131857+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"13:18 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": \"PHILLIPA YALDEN, BENN BATHGATE AND AMY CHILDS\",\n            \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n            \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"intro\": \"An unknown white powder substance delivered in an envelope addressed to the Mayor of the Rotorua Lakes Council is now undergoing forensic examination.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"Seven staffers decontaminated after Rotorua Lakes mayor mailed envelope containing white powder.\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>An unknown white powder substance delivered in an envelope addressed to the Mayor of the Rotorua Lakes Council is now undergoing forensic examination.</p> <p>Rotorua Lakes Council CEO&nbsp;Geoff Williams said at about 8:00am the envelope was opened by the call centre&nbsp;staff.</p> <p>The envelope was then quickly contained in a box and Police and Fire services were contacted.</p> <p>The building was then shut down and staff evacuated.</p> <p>Seven staff that came in contact with the envelope were decontaminated.</p> <p>&quot;This incident is being treated with serious concern although it has been suggested that it is&nbsp;unlikely&nbsp;to be hazardous material as if it was, it would have had an almost&nbsp;immediate effect,&quot; he said.</p> <p>&quot;This was quite a traumatic event for our staff. They are all fine and we are providing support, keeping in contact and following up with them.&quot;</p> <p>Mayor Steve Chadwick said this happening was out of the blue and the first incident to cause a heightened concern.</p> <p>&quot;It is very sad if there are people out there that feel so strongly. There are other ways to go about things,&quot; she said.</p> <p>&quot;I am feeling comforted in the work of Police and Fire services in that all the right things have been done.&quot;&nbsp;</p> <p>Police inspector Bruce Horne said the CIB are investigating the incident but it is still in its early stages.</p> <p>&quot;It is not known where the envelope has come from or what the substance is yet,&quot; he said.</p> <p>&quot;In 24 hours the forensic examination should be able to tell us if the powder is something to be concerned about. This will give those who were in contact with the substance peace of mind. It will take a bit longer to then find out exactly what the powder is.&quot; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p> <p>The customer centre of the council will be open again this afternoon with the call centre potentially being closed until Monday with a team from Palmerston North taking phone calls until then.&nbsp;</p> <p>There is a team from Hamilton travelling to clean the Council building thoroughly so staff are then able to return to work.</p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814670,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T124031+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:40 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Benn Bathgate\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Emergency services outside the Rotorua Lakes Council offices.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814670,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432171181/670/11814670.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814671,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T124031+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:40 21/05/2015\",\n              