//static2.stuff.co.nz/1432175727/873/11815873.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"200\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815874,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432175727/874/11815874.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815875,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T143527+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:35 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Chris Skelton/Fairfax NZ\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"fairfax-media\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Fairfax Media\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Watch the Budget speech by Finance Minister Bill English from 2pm, followed by the debate in Parliament.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815875,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432175727/875/11815875.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"220\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11815876,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T143528+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"14:35 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Chris Skelton/Fairfax NZ\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"fairfax-media\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Fairfax Media\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Watch the Budget speech by Finance Minister Bill English from 2pm, followed by the debate in Parliament.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11815876,\n                            \"layout\": \"ipad section splash 956:956\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432175728/876/11815876.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"956\",\n                            \"height\": \"955\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68738501,\n            \"path\": \"/the-press/news/68738501/Sex-addict-James-White-blackmailed-teen-victim\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/the-press/news/68738501/Sex-addict-James-White-blackmailed-teen-victim\",\n            \"section\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"section-home\": \"News\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"The Press\",\n            \"layout\": \"a-standard\",\n            \"title\": \"Sex addict James White blackmailed teen victim\",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"Sex addict blackmailed teen victim\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T131100+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"13:11 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": \"DAVID CLARKSON\",\n            \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n            \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"intro\": \"A 22-year-old who acknowledges he is a sex addict has admitted blackmail and obtaining sex by deception.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"Sex addict told male escort he'd make his life \\\"miserable\\\" and tell one person a day about him. \",\n            \"body\": \"<p>A 22-year-old who acknowledges he is a sex addict has admitted blackmail and obtaining sex by deception.</p> <p>James Charles White admitted the offences at an appearance the Christchurch District Court today.</p> <p>Judge Jane Farish convicted and remanded him on bail for sentencing on July 8. She called for a pre-sentence report to cover his suitability for a home detention sentence but warned White that he might still be jailed.</p> <p>White's blackmailing led to him being ambushed, assaulted, and robbed by the victim's friends.</p> <p>White met the blackmail victim after the 18-year-old had advertised himself as a male escort. The two exchanged emails and photographs and then met. They only knew each other on a first-name basis but began an arrangement for commercial sexual services. They would meet once a month, or sometimes as often as twice a week.</p> <p>White paid $100 for sex, later increased to $150. The arrangement continued until the victim decided to quit the sex industry and distance himself from White. He moved away from Christchurch.</p> <p>White continued texting and became increasingly more demanding, eventually telling the victim that he would find out who he was and could make his life &quot;very unpleasant&quot; and &quot;miserable&quot;.</p> <p>He sent a text saying that he would start telling one person every day what he and the victim had done and how he had been supporting himself, unless he could meet him again for sex.</p> <p>He offered up to $15,000 for more sex and the complainant agreed. Police said he was struggling financially at the time.</p> <p>They met at an abandoned house in Christchurch when White told him the figure was $150. The victim declined to have sex. White drove off and sent texts mocking the victim.</p> <p>White continued to demand that the victim meet him for sex and said he still had photographs that the student had sent him. When the threats continued, the victim arranged to meet White in Blenheim for sex.</p> <p>The victim spoke to two friends and asked for their help. He said he wanted to give White a fright and take the cellphone that contained the photographs of the student. They planned an ambush.</p> <p>White drove to Blenheim, picked up the student and drove to a remote location where the friends were waiting. They assaulted White and took his phone. The victim and his friends were all charged with aggravated robbery and have been dealt with by the courts.</p> <p>The police also told the court of White contacting a 17-year-old male through Facebook. They met for coffee and White offered him money and a car to have sex with him. The complainant accepted a $10,000 offer for sex and they engaged in several sex acts.</p> <p>When interviewed by the police, White said he had a sex addiction and was receiving help. He said he did not pay the second victim because he was not going to pay for something that &quot;didn't work&quot;.</p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814917,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T131125+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:11 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"John Kirk-Anderson\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n                    \"caption\": \"12072013 News Photo: John Kirk-Anderson / The Press / Fairfax NZ\\n\\nCourt logo district court justice generic crime punishment\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814917,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432170685/917/11814917.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"59\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814918,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T131125+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:11 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"John Kirk-Anderson\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n                    \"caption\": \"12072013 News Photo: John Kirk-Anderson / The Press / Fairfax NZ\\n\\nCourt logo district court justice generic crime punishment\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814918,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432170685/918/11814918.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"199\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814919,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432170685/919/11814919.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814920,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T131126+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:11 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"John Kirk-Anderson\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n                    \"caption\": \"12072013 News Photo: John Kirk-Anderson / The Press / Fairfax NZ\\n\\nCourt logo district court justice generic crime punishment\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814920,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432170686/920/11814920.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"220\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68373951,\n            \"path\": \"/dominion-post/news/68373951/Wellington-City-Council-forced-to-write-off-thousands-of-dollars-in-rental-debt\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/dominion-post/news/68373951/Wellington-City-Council-forced-to-write-off-thousands-of-dollars-in-rental-debt\",\n            \"section\": \"Home & Property\",\n            \"section-home\": \"News\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Dominion Post\",\n            \"layout\": \"landscape-image\",\n            \"title\": \"Wellington City Council forced to write off thousands of dollars in rental debt \",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"Unpaid council rents hit $70k\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T125834+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"12:58 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": \"NEIL RATLEY\",\n            \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n            \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"category_id\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"stream_id\": \"stuff/dominion-post/news/68373951\",\n            \"intro\": \"Wellington City Council is writing off tens of thousands of dollars each year because its tenants can't afford their rent.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"Wellington City Council has kicked out 11 tenants this year for failing to pay rent.\\n\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>Wellington City Council is writing off tens of thousands of dollars each year because its tenants can't afford their rent.</p> <p>This year the council has written off nearly $70,000 of bad debt, and evicted 11 tenants.&nbsp;</p> <p>Officials said no formal records were kept of where those tenants went,&nbsp;but the council worked with other social housing providers to secure accommodation.</p> <p>&quot;We would not intentionally send someone out to survive on the street,&quot; city housing manager Vicki McLaren said.</p> <p>But the Salvation Army said many of its clients had faced eviction from either council or private rentals.</p> <p>&quot;It doesn't take much to get behind,&quot; community ministries secretary Pam Waugh said. &quot;There could be a high electricity bill, the car could break down, or a child gets sick, and then people are forced to make a decision. Is it rent or food this week?&quot;</p> <p>Wellington city councillor Paul Eagle said many of the council's 4000 or so tenants were living on the breadline, and were only a few dollars away from being homeless.</p> <p>&quot;Alarm bells should be ringing when something like a car or appliance repairs and urgent trips or expenses for family reasons could tip someone over the edge and into a debt spiral.</p> <p>&quot;If you look at the private sector and housing affordability, we have a real problem.</p> <p>&quot;Where do those tenants who fall behind in their rent or earn just above the council housing threshold go? The alternative options are few.&quot;</p> <p>The income threshold for a council property is $869 a week, after tax, for a single adult, and $1285&nbsp;for two adults and two children.</p> <p>The council subsidises rents so that tenants pay about 70 per cent of market rates. A three-bedroom council house in suburbs between Miramar and Karori costs between $252 and $390 a week.</p> <p>In the past four years, the council has written off more than $300,000, and almost 50 people have been forced out of their council flats or houses.</p> <p>City housing operations manager&nbsp;Carol Gould said debt was written off only when tenants had not paid up for more than 12 months, and collection efforts had failed.</p> <p>Bad debt is also written off if a tenant dies. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p> <p>A council spokesman said on Thursday that, in the context of about $20 million in annual revenue collected by City Housing, this year's bad-debt writeoff of about $67,000 was well below its 2 per cent target level. &quot;We actually see [it] as a pretty impressive achievement.&quot;</p> <p>City Housing operations are not funded from rates, but entirely from rental revenue.</p> <p>Each year, the council is also forced to chase up hundreds of thousands of dollars in rent. For the 2014-15 year to date, total tenant debt stands at $334,000.</p> <p>Tenants receiving benefits are encouraged to set up automatic payments for their rent, but cannot be forced to do so.</p> <p>The best outcome for the council was to find a way to get the rent paid and avoid an eviction, Gould said. &quot;We work hard to support tenants so this situation doesn't arise and is a last resort.&quot;</p> <p>The council has been upgrading its housing since 2008, with the help of a $220m government grant. It has spent $176m of that on completing upgrades to seven complexes, and will pump in $180m of council dollars when the grant is exhausted.</p> <p><br /> </p> <p><b>By the numbers:</b></p> <p><b>Total tenant debt</b></p> <p>2011-12: $297,878</p> <p>2012-13: $279,089</p> <p>2013-14: &nbsp;$310,609</p> <p>2014-15: &nbsp;$334,234</p> <p><b>Bad Debt Writeoff&nbsp;</b></p> <p>2011-12: $50,092 &nbsp; &nbsp;</p> <p>2012-13: $114,362</p> <p>2013-14: $78,528</p> <p>2014-15: &nbsp;$67,026 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p> <p><b>Evictions</b></p> <p>2011-12: &nbsp;9</p> <p>2012-13: 16</p> <p>2013-14: 11</p> <p>2014-15: 11</p> <p><i>Source: Wellington City Council</i></p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814843,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T125954+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:59 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Kevin Stent\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-dominion-post\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Dominion Post\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Wellington City Council's Marshall Court flats in Miramar.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814843,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432169994/843/11814843.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814844,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T125954+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:59 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Kevin Stent\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-dominion-post\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Dominion Post\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Wellington City Council's Marshall Court flats in Miramar.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814844,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432169994/844/11814844.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"620\",\n                            \"height\": \"348\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814845,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T125954+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:59 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Kevin Stent\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-dominion-post\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Dominion Post\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Wellington City Council's Marshall Court flats in Miramar.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814845,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432169994/845/11814845.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"200\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814846,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432169994/846/11814846.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814847,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T125954+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:59 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Kevin Stent\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-dominion-post\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Dominion Post\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Wellington City Council's Marshall Court flats in Miramar.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814847,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432169994/847/11814847.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"220\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814848,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T125954+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:59 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Kevin Stent\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-dominion-post\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Dominion Post\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Wellington City Council's Marshall Court flats in Miramar.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814848,\n                            \"layout\": \"ipad section splash 956:956\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432169994/848/11814848.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"956\",\n                            \"height\": \"956\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68694522,\n            \"path\": \"/business/industries/68694522/Nissan-joins-Honda-and-recalls-10-300-New-Zealand-vehicles-over-faulty-airbags\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/business/industries/68694522/Nissan-joins-Honda-and-recalls-10-300-New-Zealand-vehicles-over-faulty-airbags\",\n            \"section\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"section-home\": \"Industries\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Business\",\n            \"layout\": \"landscape-image\",\n            \"title\": \"Nissan joins Honda and recalls 10,300 New Zealand vehicles over faulty airbags\",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"Nissan issues mass recall\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T125054+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"12:50 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": \"JOHN ANTHONY\",\n            \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n            \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"intro\": \"The tally for recalled cars in New Zealand because of faulty airbags has topped 50,000, with Honda and Nissan both recalling thousands more cars.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"Faulty airbag risk results in Nissan also recalling 10,300 vehicles.\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>The tally for recalled cars in New Zealand because of faulty airbags has topped 50,000, with Honda and Nissan both recalling thousands more cars.</p> <p>Nissan recalled 10,300 New Zealand vehicles as the fallout from faulty airbags spreads.&nbsp;Also on Wednesday Honda said it was recalling another 16,000 vehicles in New Zealand.</p> <p>Nissan spokesman Peter Fadeyev said&nbsp;Nissan models ranging from 2004 to 2007 were affected by faulty airbags supplied by Japanese parts manufacturer Takata.</p> <p>Details of the models and quantities in the recall were yet to be confirmed, he said.</p> <p>The company would contact customers affected by the recall as soon as parts and more details were available, he said.</p> <p>The recall would be carried out at no cost to customers.&nbsp;</p> <p>Toyota had not recalled the Avensis that Australia had recalled on Thursday afternoon. They had recalled 26,000 cars already.</p> <p>They noted that the Avensis sold in New Zealand was a different one, produced in the United Kingdom. All recall notices came directly from Toyota headquarters in Japan.</p> <p>Spokesperson Morgan Dilks said the recall process was fairly painless for consumers.</p> <p>Toyota dealers all over the country were qualified to check and replace the airbags of the affected models. This would be carried out free of charge.</p> <p>.</p> <p>The Honda recall affects New Zealand-new&nbsp;Honda Civic, Jazz, Accord Euro, and CR-Vs models ranging between 2002 and 2008 which have potentially been fitted with faulty driver or front seat passenger airbags.</p> <p>In 2014 Honda recalled 7000 vehicles in New Zealand for the same issue, taking the total recall to 23,000.</p> <p><b><i>Has your vehicle been recalled? Email us at <a target=\\\"_blank\\\" href=\\\"http://newstips@stuff.co.nz\\\">newstips@stuff.co.nz</a></i></b></p> <p>The recall is due to the potentially dangerous deployment of airbags which can send shards of metal flying with the ability to cause injury or death and is part of a worldwide recall of 4.89 million Honda's fitted with airbags from supplier Takata.</p> <p>Honda national service manager Bryan Davis said the driver and front seat passenger airbag inflators of all affected vehicles would be replaced with a new part.</p> <p>&quot;Honda New Zealand has not received any reports of incidents in New Zealand where airbags in vehicles affected by the recall might have deployed abnormally,&quot; Davis said.</p> <p>Honda New Zealand was&nbsp;checking which Japanese used imported Hondas might also be affected.</p> <p>Owners of affected vehicles, who would be identified through registration data, would be contacted by Honda New Zealand, he said.</p> <p>AA motoring advice manager Andrew Bayliss said: &quot;Despite the very small risk, any safety related defect must be treated seriously, but there is no need to panic,&quot; Bayliss said.</p> <p>Given the numbers of vehicles affected, it was unlikely that parts would be available immediately, he said.</p> <p>A reported&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/motoring/news/68691560/air-bag-maker-recalls-34-million-vehicles-in-us\\\">34 million affected vehicles in the United States</a>&nbsp;could potentially be recalled.</p> <p>Various Japanese car makers were affected by the fault with Toyota and Nissan having issued vehicle recalls globally, Bayliss said.</p> <p>Earlier in May Toyota New Zealand&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/motoring/news/68534534/toyota-new-zealand-recalls-cars\\\">recalled 26,000 Corolla, Picnic, Yaris and RAV4 vehicles for a possible airbag fault.</a>&nbsp;as part of a&nbsp;worldwide recall of 5 million Toyotas fitted with Takata airbags.</p> <p>Toyota spokesman Morgan Dilks said Toyota New Zealand was waiting to hear from its head office in Japan if there would be further recalls.</p> <p>Last year Mazda New Zealand recalled 5100&nbsp;New Zealand-new Mazda 6 cars sold in 2002 and 2003 and the used Japanese-import version Mazda Atenza, with front passenger airbags made by Takata.</p> <p>Mazda general manager of vehicle sales and marketing Glenn Harris said on Wednesday Mazda was also waiting to hear from its global head office in Japan if the recall would be extended.</p> <div> <span>&nbsp;</span> </div>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814781,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T125112+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:51 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": null,\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-press\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Press\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Honda is recalling an additional 16,000 vehicles in New Zealand due to faulty airbags.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814781,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432169472/781/11814781.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"59\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814782,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T125112+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:51 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": null,\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-press\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Press\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Honda is recalling an additional 16,000 vehicles in New Zealand due to faulty airbags.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814782,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432169472/782/11814782.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"620\",\n                            \"height\": \"348\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814783,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T125112+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:51 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": null,\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-press\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Press\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Honda is recalling an additional 16,000 vehicles in New Zealand due to faulty airbags.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814783,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432169472/783/11814783.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"199\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814784,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432169472/784/11814784.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814785,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T125112+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:51 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": null,\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-press\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Press\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Honda is recalling an additional 16,000 vehicles in New Zealand due to faulty airbags.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814785,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432169472/785/11814785.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"220\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814786,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T125112+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:51 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": null,\n                    \"source_code\": \"the-press\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"The Press\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Honda is recalling an additional 16,000 vehicles in New Zealand due to faulty airbags.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814786,\n                            \"layout\": \"ipad section splash 956:956\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432169472/786/11814786.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"955\",\n                            \"height\": \"955\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68737091,\n            \"path\": \"/entertainment/tv-radio/68737091/Bill-Murray-falls-off-his-chair-in-drunken-TV-interview\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/entertainment/tv-radio/68737091/Bill-Murray-falls-off-his-chair-in-drunken-TV-interview\",\n            \"section\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"section-home\": \"TV & Radio\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Entertainment\",\n            \"layout\": \"landscape-video\",\n            \"title\": \"Bill Murray falls off his chair in drunken TV interview\",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"Drunk Bill Murray falls off chair \",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T124708+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"12:47 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": null,\n            \"source_code\": \"aap\",\n            \"source_name\": \"AAP\",\n            \"intro\": \"Bill Murray has slurred his words and fallen off a chair during a drunken interview on a US news programme.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"In the battle of celebrity versus chair, Bill Murray is the biggest loser. And he blames David Letterman.\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>Bill Murray has slurred his words and fallen off a chair during a drunken interview on a US news programme.<br /> <br /> The Groundhog Day&nbsp;star appeared on&nbsp;The Last Word&nbsp;with Lawrence O'Donnell, just hours after he had taped his&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/entertainment/david-letterman-retires-after-33-years-as-host-of-the-late-show-20150520-gh65a3.html\\\">final appearance on&nbsp;</a><a href=\\\"http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/entertainment/david-letterman-retires-after-33-years-as-host-of-the-late-show-20150520-gh65a3.html\\\">The Late Show with David Letterman</a>&nbsp;in New York City.<br /> <br /> <b>ALSO READ:&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/tv-radio/68728747/why-david-letterman-is-among-television-historys-biggest-losers\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Why David Letterman is among television history's biggest losers<br /> <br /> </a></b>While O'Donnell promoted Murray's appearance, the camera cut to the actor, who tried to sit on a raised chair but leaned too far back, causing it to topple over and sending Murray crashing to the floor.<br /> <br /> <img src=\\\"http://images.brisbanetimes.com.au/2015/05/21/6549035/Article%20Lead%20-%20wide996308114gh64pfimage.related.articleLeadwide.729x410.gh6c9e.png1432168019754.jpg-620x349.jpg\\\" alt=\\\"David Letterman and Bill Murray at the taping of the debut of &lt;i&gt;Late Night with David Letterman&lt;/i&gt; in New York in 1982.\\\" /></p> <p><br /> David Letterman and Bill Murray at the taping of the debut of&nbsp;<i>Late Night with David Letterman</i>&nbsp;in New York in 1982.&nbsp;<i>Photo: NANCY KAYE<br /> <br /> </i>&quot;I just did the Letterman show, then I went to dinner and had oysters, rose wine, red wine, duck, grass-fed hanger steak, and then rushed here to do your show just because Jim said that you wanted (me) to come on the show,&quot; he said after a commercial break.<br /> <br /> The comedian had&nbsp;celebrated with Letterman hours earlier, jumping out of a giant cake and swigging from a bottle of vodka.<br /> <br /> After the on-air stumble, Murray quickly launched into a blame game.</p> <p>In slurred speech and struggling to form sentences, Murray said, &quot;Your girls here... those brutal... I don't know where you get these women that push people around... they pushed me in a chair and the chair was not balanced properly and I went down and hurt myself properly.&quot;</p> <p>It remains unclear who it was that Murray was referring to in his complaint.</p> <p>According to the show's website, 11 of 18 staffers at&nbsp;The Last Word&nbsp;are women, not including camera operators.</p> <p>When asked about Murray's comments, an&nbsp;MSNBC&nbsp;spokesperson told&nbsp;The Washington Post, &quot;We're not sure what Bill meant by those comments – we'd suggest asking him, if you&nbsp;haven't&nbsp;already.&quot;</p> <p>In his Letterman appearance earlier in the day, Murray went from Ghostbuster to cake buster after jumping from a giant cake.</p> <p>Murray was the first ever guest on Letterman's&nbsp;Late Night Show&nbsp;in 1982.</p> <p>In his farewell to the 68-year-old host, Murray donned a set of overalls and protective goggles before jumping out of the cake, emblazoned with the words 'Goodbye Dave'.</p> <p>He then took great joy in rubbing the host's suit and hair with cream.&nbsp;</p> <p><i>Letterman's final show is screened in New Zealand on Prime on Thursday night at 9.30pm&nbsp;</i></p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814744,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T124736+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:47 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": null,\n                    \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Bill Murray falls of a chair during an apparently drunken interview\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814744,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432170042/744/11814744.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814849,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T130043+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:00 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"YouTube\",\n                    \"caption\": \"In the battle of celebrity versus chair, the latter wins.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814849,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432170043/849/11814849.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814850,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T130043+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:00 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"YouTube\",\n                    \"caption\": \"In the battle of celebrity versus chair, the latter wins.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814850,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432170043/850/11814850.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"620\",\n                            \"height\": \"348\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814851,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T130043+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:00 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"YouTube\",\n                    \"caption\": \"In the battle of celebrity versus chair, the latter wins.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814851,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432170043/851/11814851.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"199\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814852,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432170043/852/11814852.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814853,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T130043+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:00 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"YouTube\",\n                    \"caption\": \"In the battle of celebrity versus chair, the latter wins.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814853,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432170043/853/11814853.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"219\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814854,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T130043+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"13:00 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"YouTube\",\n                    \"caption\": \"In the battle of celebrity versus chair, the latter wins.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814854,\n                            \"layout\": \"ipad section splash 956:956\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432170043/854/11814854.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"956\",\n                            \"height\": \"956\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ],\n            \"videos\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814659,\n                    \"layout\": \"Standard Video\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"aap\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"AAP\",\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T123935+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:39 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"VideoSource/YouTube\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Bill Murray falls of a chair during an apparently drunken interview \",\n                    \"src\": \"http://file2.stuff.co.nz/1432168775/660/11814660.mp4\",\n                    \"video_poster\": {\n                        \"id\": 11814661,\n                        \"layout\": \"Video Image\",\n                        \"src\": \"http://file2.stuff.co.nz/1432170043/661/11814661.jpg\",\n                        \"width\": \"640\",\n                        \"height\": \"360\"\n                    }\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68729562,\n            \"path\": \"/auckland/local-news/68729562/Drunk-driver-killed-passenger-during-police-chase\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/auckland/local-news/68729562/Drunk-driver-killed-passenger-during-police-chase\",\n            \"section\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"section-home\": \"Local News\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Auckland\",\n            \"layout\": \"landscape-image\",\n            \"title\": \"Drunk driver killed passenger during police chase\",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"Drunk in high-speed police chase\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T123220+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"12:32 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": \"IAN STEWARD\",\n            \"intro\": \"A drunk-driver who crashed and killed his passenger during a police chase has been jailed for five years.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"A drunk-driver who crashed and killed his passenger during a police chase has been jailed for five years.\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>A drunk-driver who crashed and killed his passenger during a police chase has been jailed for five years.</p> <p>Robert Pora appeared in the High Court at Auckland on Thursday where he was sentenced by Justice Ailsa Duffy for the manslaughter of Steven Henare Te Pania.</p> <p>Pora had earlier pleaded guilty to manslaughter, reckless driving causing injury, driving under the influence of alcohol, failing to stop for police and being an unlicensed driver.</p> <p>Justice Duffy said at about 9.30pm on August 15, 2014, Pora was driving a Mitsubishi car on Puhinui Rd, Manukau, with Te Pania in the front passenger seat.</p> <p>Police saw Pora overtake another vehicle at speed on the suburban road and started a chase, with their lights and sirens activated.</p> <p>The chase reached speeds up to 100kmh, and Pora went through the busy Great South Rd-Puhinui Rd intersection on the wrong side of the road against a red light. &nbsp;</p> <p>In Boundary Rd, he turned his headlights off, but as he went to overtake a vehicle he hit the centre traffic island.</p> <p>&quot;The Mitsubishi has travelled out of control down the wrong side of the road before colliding with an oncoming vehicle,&quot; police said.</p> <p>The car flipped on to its side, and Te Pania was killed in the impact.</p> <p>Pora was extracted from the car by police and ambulance staff and taken to hospital with life-threatening injuries.</p> <p>The driver of the car Pora hit suffered an injury to his left shoulder and was discharged from hospital the following day.</p> <p>Pora was found to have a level of 115 to 127 milligrams of alcohol per 100 millilitres of blood, when the legal limit was 80mg.</p> <p>His car was found to have no warrant of fitness or registration.</p> <p>Police said Pora admitted responsibility for the crash, saying he had been drinking before the incident and he was driving at speeds &quot;way over the limit&quot;.</p> <p>He admitted knowing there were deficiencies with the car's tyres and engine, and that he was forbidden to drive.</p> <p>&quot;He complained that the [deceased] had encouraged him to drive off at speed to 'lose' the police during the initial stages of the pursuit,&quot; the police summary said.&nbsp;</p> <p>Victim impact statements were read to the court ​but their contents were suppressed.</p> <p>A letter Pora had written was also read in which he ​said he had caused the death of a close friend &quot;all because of my stupid actions and silly behaviour&quot;.</p> <p>&quot;I am truly sorry. I truly regret every minute of it...I truly want to apologise to Steven's family.&quot;</p> <p>&quot;To my bro Steven, if your spirit is here with us today, I want to tell you I'm truly sorry and for the the pain I've caused your family. You will always remain in my heart. I love you my bro and please know how truly sorry I am for everything.&quot;​</p> <p>Justice Duffy said Pora had previous convictions for dangerous driving, failing to stop for police and driving while unlicensed and forbidden.</p> <p>He was &quot;impecunious&quot; and had no way of paying reparations, she said.</p> <p>She gave him a sentence discount of five per cent for his genuine remorse and sentenced him to five years in prison.</p> <p>He will be banned from driving for three years once he is released.</p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814612,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T123257+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:32 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Ian Steward\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"sunday-star-times\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Sunday Star Times\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Robert Pora in the High Court at Auckland on Thursday.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814612,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432168377/612/11814612.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"59\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814613,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T123257+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:32 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Ian Steward\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"sunday-star-times\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Sunday Star Times\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Robert Pora in the High Court at Auckland on Thursday.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814613,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432168377/613/11814613.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"620\",\n                            \"height\": \"349\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814614,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T123257+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:32 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Ian Steward\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"sunday-star-times\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Sunday Star Times\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Robert Pora in the High Court at Auckland on Thursday.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814614,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432168377/614/11814614.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"200\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814615,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432168377/615/11814615.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814616,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T123257+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:32 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Ian Steward\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"sunday-star-times\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Sunday Star Times\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Robert Pora in the High Court at Auckland on Thursday.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814616,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432168377/616/11814616.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"220\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814617,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T123257+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:32 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Ian Steward\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"sunday-star-times\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Sunday Star Times\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Robert Pora in the High Court at Auckland on Thursday.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814617,\n                            \"layout\": \"ipad section splash 956:956\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432168377/617/11814617.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"955\",\n                            \"height\": \"955\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68725628,\n            \"path\": \"/life-style/home-property/68725628/Government-to-devote-430-hectares-to-help-solve-Auckland-housing-crisis\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/life-style/home-property/68725628/Government-to-devote-430-hectares-to-help-solve-Auckland-housing-crisis\",\n            \"section\": \"Politics\",\n            \"section-home\": \"Home & Property\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Life & Style\",\n            \"layout\": \"landscape-image\",\n            \"title\": \"Government to devote 430 hectares to help solve Auckland housing crisis \",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"430 hectares to help Auckland housing\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T120228+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"12:02 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": \"HAMISH RUTHERFORD AND JO MOIR\",\n            \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n            \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"category_id\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"stream_id\": \"stuff/life-style/home-property/68725628\",\n            \"intro\": \"Details of a housing plan to help solve Auckland's surging property prices were revealed on a Ministry website ahead of the Budget, but there are no red faces about it says the Housing Minister.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"The Goverment is looking to use land once earmarked for schools and hospitals for housing.\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>Details of a housing plan to help solve Auckland's surging property prices were revealed on a Ministry website ahead of the Budget, but there are no red faces about it says the Housing Minister.</p> <p>Officials have been examining what the Crown owns, which is now surplus to needs, as the Government looks to use 430 hectares of reserves, defence land and property once earmarked for schools and hospitals to develop housing to be sold.</p> <p>Labour has dismissed the plan as dusting off old policy seven years too late.</p> <p>Although the process was planned to be announced as part of Thursday's Budget, details of the plans to bring in private sector companies were added to the Ministry of Business, Innovation and Employment website on Tuesday.</p> <p>But Housing Minister Nick Smith said he instructed the Ministry to push ahead with inviting interested parties to a function next week.</p> <p>&quot;I'm not at all concerned about it - in fact I was in Christchurch some weeks ago and spoke to media and indicated the Government was proceeding with a similar programme in Auckland,&quot; he told Radio NZ.</p> <p>He said it was only the amount set aside in the Budget for the housing initiative that was being kept under wraps.</p> <p><b>SO WHAT LAND WILL BE DEVELOPED?&nbsp;</b></p> <p>An initial invitation to take part in a tender to develop housing on Crown land in Auckland says that the ministry will conduct &quot;an open contestable process to identify a shortlist of suitably qualified parties or consortia with the capability and capacity to deliver housing developments at pace in Auckland&quot;.</p> <p>Land being considered for development and sale includes farmland, that held by tertiary institutions, health boards, the defence force, holdings of Housing New Zealand and even land designated as reserves owned by the Department of Conservation.</p> <p>Smith wouldn't confirm how many houses would be built on the 430 hectares of land being put aside for the development other than to say it would certainly be in the thousands.</p> <p>&quot;It's a very large mix and there's a significant amount of it,&quot; Smith said. While there some &quot;very precious nature reserves&quot; which would never be considered for sale, many others were effectively vacant.</p> <p>&quot;You'd be quite astounded by some areas of reserves - and when you say the word reserve you assume that's a park and somebody using it - of land that's effectively vacant and being under utilised,&quot; he said. Some land zoned as reserves <g class=\\\"gr_ gr_103 gr-alert gr_gramm Grammar multiReplace\\\" data-gr-id=\\\"103\\\"> was </g> currently being used as a construction yard, he said.</p> <p>&quot;What I've been surprised by is how poorly government agencies generally manage their land holdings, that you can have quite significant blocks of land sitting around unused &nbsp;for large periods and so I'm having a close and hard look at where there are land holdings, held by government agencies that will help deal with the challenges over housing that we have in Auckland.&quot;</p> <p>Land which the Government was developing in Weymouth had been held for the Ministry of Education and then the Ministry of Social Development for more than 20 years &quot;during which period there was high housing need in South Auckland. Frankly, government agencies should have gone into action a lot earlier in utilising that land&quot;.</p> <p><b>READ MORE: <br /> <a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/life-style/home-property/68710603/could-the-government-fund-more-housing-using-foreign-money\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">*Could the government fund more housing using foreign money?<br /> </a><a href=\\\"http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/Budget-2015.html\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">*Full coverage: Budget 2015</a></b></p> <p>There would be some issues to overcome with local iwi due to the restraints on some of the land around <g class=\\\"gr_ gr_88 gr-alert gr_gramm Grammar only-ins replaceWithoutSep\\\" data-gr-id=\\\"88\\\"> first </g> right of refusal, Smith told Radio NZ.</p> <p>It was an issue that would need to be worked through in the same way that the Government would be looking at land set aside for schools that hadn't seen any development in 20 years.</p> <p>&quot;The key issue for Government is where there is no obvious use in the next 10 to 15 years, could it be used for housing.&quot;</p> <p>Labour housing spokesman Phil Twyford said National's plans were simply a dusting &quot;off Labour's 2008 inventory of government land available for housing&quot; and re-announced it.</p> <p>&quot;Despite National ridiculing this at the time, it is a no-brainer to develop vacant government land in Auckland,&quot; Twyford said</p> <p>&quot;The Government should have continued Labour's work in this area seven years ago. If it had, we would have had thousands of new homes and the housing crisis might not be as bad.</p> <p>Twyford said given the lack of action over seven years, the addition of 430 hectares of Crown land is unlikely to have much effect on house prices.</p> <p>&quot;A shortfall of 20,000 homes has built up under this Government. Auckland needs 13,000 a year just to keep up with population growth and consent figures show a build rate of less than 8000 a year,&quot; Twyford said.</p> <p>&quot;The shortage is getting worse by the day, which is why house prices went up more than $100,000 in the past year.&quot;</p> <p>Green Party co-leader Metiria Turei said the Government must guarantee 100 <g class=\\\"gr_ gr_84 gr-alert gr_spell ContextualSpelling ins-del\\\" data-gr-id=\\\"84\\\"> per cent </g> of the homes built on the 430 hectares would be dedicated affordable housing - the housing crisis wouldn't be fixed by building houses that Aucklanders couldn't afford to buy. &nbsp;</p> <p>&quot;They must not sell it off to private developers for private purposes - it is public land, it should be used for affordable housing for New Zealanders who are struggling.</p> <p>&quot;What constitutes affordable, of course, <g class=\\\"gr_ gr_82 gr-alert gr_gramm Grammar only-ins replaceWithoutSep\\\" data-gr-id=\\\"82\\\"> depends </g> - the Government seems to think that New Zealand families can afford a house of over half a million dollars - that's just simply not true.&quot;</p> <p>The Government needed to invest in building affordable homes that were about three or four times the average wage, Turei said. &nbsp;</p> <p>&quot;Part of the problem in Auckland now is that property developers have no incentive to build houses to be sold at anything other than market rates – that's why the Government needs to step in and make it a condition of the land development that they're not.&quot;</p> <p>The Government had had the land the whole time it had been in power, and had been <g class=\\\"gr_ gr_80 gr-alert gr_spell ContextualSpelling\\\" data-gr-id=\\\"80\\\"> berating </g> Auckland Council about releasing land for housing while &quot;sitting on a gold mine which they could have been using for years now to build housing.&quot;</p> <p>&quot;So it's disgraceful that they've come to this so late, but the fact is, they have land, it's public land, they need to engage in building homes that are affordable and available to low-income New Zealanders.&quot;</p> <p>The Budget was the Government's chance to &quot;finally do something meaningful on housing,&quot; Turei said.</p>\",\n            \"images\": [\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814229,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T120306+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:03 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Bruce Mercer\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"waikato-times\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Waikato Times\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Housing Minister Nick Smith said he instructed Ministry of Business, Innovation and Employment to push ahead with a housing policy ahead of it being announced in the Budget.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814229,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432166586/229/11814229.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814230,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T120306+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:03 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Bruce Mercer\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"waikato-times\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Waikato Times\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Housing Minister Nick Smith said he instructed Ministry of Business, Innovation and Employment to push ahead with a housing policy ahead of it being announced in the Budget.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814230,\n                            \"layout\": \"Standard Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432166586/230/11814230.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"620\",\n                            \"height\": \"349\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814231,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T120306+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:03 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Bruce Mercer\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"waikato-times\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Waikato Times\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Housing Minister Nick Smith said he instructed Ministry of Business, Innovation and Employment to push ahead with a housing policy ahead of it being announced in the Budget.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814231,\n                            \"layout\": \"Strap Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432166586/231/11814231.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"300\",\n                            \"height\": \"200\"\n                        },\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814232,\n                            \"layout\": \"Small Thumbnail\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432166586/232/11814232.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"90\",\n                            \"height\": \"60\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814233,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T120306+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:03 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Bruce Mercer\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"waikato-times\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Waikato Times\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Housing Minister Nick Smith said he instructed Ministry of Business, Innovation and Employment to push ahead with a housing policy ahead of it being announced in the Budget.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814233,\n                            \"layout\": \"Defcon Image\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432166586/233/11814233.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"418\",\n                            \"height\": \"220\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                },\n                {\n                    \"id\": 11814234,\n                    \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T120306+1200\",\n                    \"datetime_display\": \"12:03 21/05/2015\",\n                    \"creditline\": \"Bruce Mercer\",\n                    \"source_code\": \"waikato-times\",\n                    \"source_name\": \"Waikato Times\",\n                    \"caption\": \"Housing Minister Nick Smith said he instructed Ministry of Business, Innovation and Employment to push ahead with a housing policy ahead of it being announced in the Budget.\",\n                    \"variants\": [\n                        {\n                            \"id\": 11814234,\n                            \"layout\": \"ipad section splash 956:956\",\n                            \"src\": \"http://static2.stuff.co.nz/1432166586/234/11814234.jpg\",\n                            \"media_type\": \"Photo\",\n                            \"width\": \"955\",\n                            \"height\": \"955\"\n                        }\n                    ]\n                }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"id\": 68733779,\n            \"path\": \"/sport/rugby/all-blacks/68733779/New-Zealand-Rugby-fights-Brazil-clothing-company-over-use-of-fern\",\n            \"url\": \"http://www.stuff.co.nz/_json/sport/rugby/all-blacks/68733779/New-Zealand-Rugby-fights-Brazil-clothing-company-over-use-of-fern\",\n            \"section\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"section-home\": \"All Blacks\",\n            \"section-top-level\": \"Sport\",\n            \"layout\": \"landscape-image\",\n            \"title\": \"New Zealand Rugby fights Brazil clothing company over use of fern\",\n            \"subhead\": null,\n            \"alt_headline\": \"NZR in battle over kimono\",\n            \"datetime_iso8601\": \"20150521T115911+1200\",\n            \"datetime_display\": \"11:59 21/05/2015\",\n            \"byline\": null,\n            \"source_code\": \"1national-newsroom\",\n            \"source_name\": \"Stuff\",\n            \"intro\": \"New Zealand Rugby are ordering a Brazilian company to remove a fern from a martial arts uniform being marketed globally online.\",\n            \"alt_intro\": \"Trademark issues at centre of New Zealand Rugby complaint against Brazilian martial arts apparel firm.\",\n            \"body\": \"<p>New Zealand Rugby are ordering a Brazilian company to remove a fern from a martial arts uniform being marketed globally online.</p> <p>The &quot;haka kimono&quot; features the fern and Maori-inspired motifs in its black and white design, manufactured by Sao Paulo-based&nbsp; KVRA Clothing.</p> <p>New Zealand Rugby have trademarked the silver fern and have strenuously protected that over the years. The silver fern is also used in the marketing of the kimono which sell for more than $250 online.</p> <p>New Zealand Rugby confirmed they will ask for the fern to be removed by the Brazilian company.</p> <p>Brazil is to be the scene of rugby history next year when sevens makes its Olympics debut in Rio de Janeiro.</p> <p>New Zealand have qualified both their men's and women's teams for the Olympics and each are considered strong medal favourites. Their uniforms will feature the silver fern.</p> <p>Maori experts have also questioned the use of a moko on a skull in the uniform's design, believing that could be offensive.</p><p><style>.html-asset {clear:both;}</style><blockquote class=\\\"instagram-media\\\" data-instgrm-captioned data-instgr